RIOS.name: Academy
RIOS.description:
The Academy for Creative Media Student Association (ACMSA) is a Registered Independent Organization (RIO) at the University of Hawaii Manoa (UHM).

The ACMSA is the student association for the Academy for Creative Media (ACM) which is an undergraduate bachelor's program at UHM.  ACM falls under the College of Arts & Humanities.

We strive to connect ACM Student filmmakers with each other and others in the community to collaborate and produce student films.

RIOS.name: Accounting Club at UH Manoa
RIOS.description: Established in 1964, the Accounting Club is a proud student chapter of the Institute of Management Accountants.

RIOS.name: Adventist Christian Fellowship
RIOS.description: Adventist Christian Fellowship is about the mission of God through the Seventh-day Adventist Church on college and university campuses in the North America Division.

RIOS.name: Advocates for Public Interest Law
RIOS.description: Advocates for Public Interest Law is an organization within the Hawai'i legal community whose purpose is to encourage public interest legal work.

RIOS.name: American Association of University Women - University of Hawaii at Manoa
RIOS.description: AAUW Honolulu was founded in 1905 as the College Club. Created to promote “the higher ideals of education among women” it became an official branch of the American Association of University Women in 1922.

RIOS.name: Association for Educational Communications and Technology-Hawaii
RIOS.description: The Association for Educational Communications and Technology (AECT) is a professional association of thousands of educators and others whose activities are directed toward improving instruction through technology.

RIOS.name: Aikido @ UHM
RIOS.description: The Aikido Club at UHM was founded by Robert Little Sensei (5th dan) and is affiliated with the Hawaii Aikido Federation. Little Sensei is the chief instructor of the club. Visitors are welcome and classes are always open to beginning students.

RIOS.name: Alpha Gamma Delta, Delta Sigma Chapter
RIOS.description: Alpha Gamma Delta is an international women's fraternity that promotes academic excellence, philanthropic giving, ongoing leadership, personal development, and above all, a spirit of loving sisterhood. Guided by our Purpose, Alpha Gams strive to attain a higher standard, thereby improving their lives, the lives of those around them and the communities in which they live. Together, we continually work to inspire the woman and impact the world.

RIOS.name: Alpha Sigma Phi
RIOS.description: The Fraternity aims to be the co-curricular organization of choice for discerning undergraduate men through the provision of an enriching brotherhood experience and a full range of character and leadership development opportunities.

RIOS.name: AlohaNation Flowarts
RIOS.description: To provide a safe place to foster the growth of different flow art styles such as gloving, orbiting, hooping, poi, etc. We hope to provide a venue for UH Manoa students to practice their art, compete, and hold events. If you do any flow arts or are interested in learning about one, please consider joining the AlohaNation Flowarts RIO at UH Manoa!

RIOS.name: AMA/HMA Student Chapter at JABSOM
RIOS.description: UHM student chapter for the AMA and the HMA.

RIOS.name: American Cetacean Society Student Coalition at University of Hawaii at Manoa
RIOS.description: The mission of the American Cetacean Society Student Coalition at the University of Hawai’i at Manoa is to focus on the conservation of the world’s oceanic habitats, specifically those of whales, dolphins, and porpoises, through experience, education, service, and outreach.

RIOS.name: American Indian Science and Engineering Society
RIOS.description: The American Indian Science and Engineering Society is an international professional organization that works to increase the representation of American Indians, Alaska Natives, Native Hawaiians, and other indigenous people in the STEM field.

RIOS.name: American Institute of Architecture Students
RIOS.description:
VISION: Empowering voices, ideas, and actions for the future
MISSION: Advancing leadership, design, and service among architecture students

RIOS.name: American Library Association Student Chapter
RIOS.description: Aloha! Welcome to the American Library Association Student Chapter Website at the University of Hawaii at Manoa.  Our student chapter is committed to celebrating and promoting the library and information science profession.  Our members plan events and activities that encourage professional development, service to the library community, fundraising, socializing and networking.

RIOS.name: American Marketing Association
RIOS.description: Adventure Awaits with AMA embodies the opportunities that we will go for as a chapter throughout the year. With the support and empowerment of each member in AMA, we will all help one another reach our goals and find ourselves. The American Marketing Association at UHM is about creating connections, strengthening bonds, and growing in personal and professional ways. Together, we will endure, succeed, and grow.

RIOS.name: American Meterological Society Aloha Chapter
RIOS.description: The American Meteorological Society (AMS) is the nation’s premier scientific and professional organization promoting and disseminating information about the atmospheric, oceanic, and hydrologic sciences. Members include researchers, educators, students, enthusiasts, broadcasters and other professionals in weather, water, and climate.

RIOS.name: American Society of Civil Engineers
RIOS.description: The American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) student chapter at the University of Hawaii at Manoa is a proud organization geared towards promoting the civil engineering profession and providing a better understanding of the field outside of the classroom. From memorable socials and fundraisers to sharing triumphs in activities such as steel bridge and concrete canoe, the student chapter is ideal for meeting, as well as bonding with fellow aspiring civil engineers. Not only is the student chapter a prime source for developing new and lasting relationships, but it is also a gateway for expanding a student's network through frequent interactions with the ASCE Hawaii Section and the Young Member Forum (YMF). Inspirational speakers from an immense spectrum of engineering firms and companies also takes part in our general meetings to further educate and enlighten students about the civil engineering world.

RIOS.name: American Society of Mechanical Engineers
RIOS.description: The American Society of Mechanical Engineers at the University of Hawai'i at Mānoa is dedicated to servicing the mechanical engineering students of UHM.

RIOS.name: American Society for Microbiology Hawaii Student Chapter
RIOS.description: Aloha ! Welcome to the Hawaiʻi Chapter of the American Society for Microbiology (HI-ASM). HI-ASM brings together microbiologists from various island institutions such as universities, hospitals, government agencies, the military and biotechnology companies. Our geographic location provides us with opportunities and challenges unique to our island state that emphasize the importance of a cohesive community of microbiologists.

RIOS.name: Anesthesiology Interest Group
RIOS.description: JABSOM AIG is an online portal for medical students at the University of Hawai'i so that they may learn more about careers in anesthesiology. Our AIG officers and advising faculty work to organize events and maintain online resources that are both applicable and high-yield to students interested in anesthesiology.

RIOS.name: Animal Science Club
RIOS.description: UHM club for the people in the animal sciences.

RIOS.name: Anthropology Undergraduate Student Association
RIOS.description: AUSA is a student-led organization that provides undergraduate majors and non-majors with opportunities to learn more about anthropology, participate in networking events for students with interests in anthropology, participate in community service events, and find out about field school, grants, fellowships, and research opportunities of interest to anthropology students.

RIOS.name: Artists and Musicians at JABSOM
RIOS.description: JABSOM Artists & Musicians (JAM) is a student interest group at the University of Hawai‘i John A. Burns School of Medicine that unites individuals in medicine with talents in art and music.  Founded in 2015, JAM was created after noticing the struggle of finding student performers for JABSOM-related events such as the Senior Lu'au and Willed Body Ceremony. There was certainly no lack of talent, rather the lack of a network to recognize and bring together those with creative talents, which is easily forgotten in the midst of endless exams and long hours on the wards.  Thus, medical students Christina Wu, Caroline Ritson, and Leimomi Kanagusuku worked together to create a group that would help rekindle the passion for "right-brain" activities that are fun, therapeutic, and inspiring, but also bring together those with diverse talents and great potential to impact the community beyond the practice of medicine.

RIOS.name: Associated Students at JABSOM
RIOS.description: UHM club for the students of the JABSOM.

RIOS.name: Association For Computing Machinery at Manoa
RIOS.description: We, the Association for Computing Machinery at UH Manoa (ACManoa/ACM), are the largest computer science student organization at the University of Hawaii at Manoa.  We are a registered student chapter of the Association for Computing Machinery as well as a recognized student-chartered registered independent organization (RIO) at the University of Hawaii at Manoa. We welcome students of all different backgrounds, interests, and skill levels to join our community and share our passion for computer science.

RIOS.name: Atherton YMCA
RIOS.description: The Atherton Y uses the power of friendship and fellowship to nurture the potential of every individual; creating opportunities for everyone to learn, grow, and thrive together as we positively impact communities.

RIOS.name: Athletic Training Student Society
RIOS.description: UHM club for students in the athletic training degree.

RIOS.name: Autonomous Control Theory-Unmanned Aerial Systems
RIOS.description: The Autonomous Control Technologies – Unmanned Aerial Systems (ACTUAS) project has been recently funded through a NASA EPSCoR (National Aeronautics and Space Administration Established Program to Simulate Competitive Research) grant and is a RIO (Registered Independent Organization) at the University of Hawai’i at Mānoa. This project involves unmanned aerial systems (UAS) where the students learn about UAS kinematics, dynamics, navigation, guidance and control, and conduct simulations, assemble, integrate and fly UASs, such as a fixed‐wing aircraft, a quadcopter and other multi‐rotor systems for a wide range of applications. Dr. Azimov is the Science Principal Investigator of the ACTUAS Project, and ACTUAS currently serves as one of the main projects in Hawai`i’s Engaged STEM Pathways (HESTEMP) program.

RIOS.name: Bachelor of Social Work Organization
RIOS.description: UHM club for students in the social work degrees.

RIOS.name: Baha'i Association at UH Manoa
RIOS.description: UHM club for people of the Baha'i faith.

RIOS.name: Baptist College Ministries
RIOS.description: Baptist Collegiate Ministries (BCM) O‘ahu exists to lead college students to an authentic and growing relationship with Jesus Christ that produces in them a passion for God, a desire to live holy, and a vision to impact their campuses and the world.

RIOS.name: Belly Dance Raqs- Manoa
RIOS.description: Our organization is centered on the idea of learning dance for dance's sake. We encourage dancers to learn to create their own choreography and to develop independence and confidence as soloists in addition to being able to dance together collaboratively. Explore, create, seek out other dance experiences, and develop your unique and beautiful dance identity! We also have a sister organization at UH West Oahu.

RIOS.name: Best Buddies Hawaii-UH Manoa/SAAC Chapter
RIOS.description: Best Buddies Hawaii creates opportunities for one-to-one friendship, integrated employment and leadership skill building for individuals with developmental disabilities. SAAC helped to create the University of Hawaii Manoa chapter to offer its members opportunities for peer friendships and community engagement.

RIOS.name: Beta Alpha Psi, Delta Theta Chapter
RIOS.description: Beta Alpha Psi is an honors organization for financial information students and professionals. The organization's mission is to complement each member's formal education by providing interactions among students, faculty, and professionals and foster lifelong growth, services and ethical conduct.

RIOS.name: Beta Beta Gamma Sorority
RIOS.description: The Beta Beta Gamma Sorority is a cosmopolitan Greek fraternal organization at the University of Hawaii at Manoa. It was founded in 1948 for the development of leadership, community service, long lasting friendships, and career planning through alumnae relations.

RIOS.name: Black Law Students Association
RIOS.description: The National Black Law Students Association (NBLSA), founded in 1968, is a national organization formed to articulate and promote the needs and goals of black law students and effectuate change in the legal community.

RIOS.name: Blue Zones Project
RIOS.description: Blue Zones Project® is a community well-being initiative that makes healthy choices easier in all the places we live, work and play.

RIOS.name: Botanical Society of America Hawaii Chapter
RIOS.description: This is the official page for the Botanical Society of America (BSA), University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa Student Chapter.

RIOS.name: Buddhi Yoga Manoa
RIOS.description: We get together and do buddhi! We get together weekly to work out and have fun! Buddhi is a high intensity workout that blends practices of yoga, dance, plyometrics, kundalini and meditation. Ever wanted to let loose and break it down without going to the club? Get your groove on in a no judgment space and work it out just for you? Buddhi is for you. Invented on the Big Island, the buddhi practice is an amazing way to meet health and fun oriented people throughout the islands and worldwide. We will be organizing a retreat for our members this year.

RIOS.name: Business Executive Society of Tomorrow
RIOS.description: The Business Executive Society of Tomorrow is a general business club at the University of Hawaii at Manoa’s Shidler College of Business. Founded by students in 1998, BEST has a proud history of maintaining and perpetuating excellence in its members. Through the years, we have developed a culture of diligence and dedication to personal and professional growth. Through a combination of tours, workshops, networking events, alumni events, community services, and socials, we strive to mold our members into well-rounded individuals. We pride ourselves in producing the business leaders of tomorrow, and we provide our members with ample opportunities to continually advance toward that goal.

RIOS.name: Campus Drummers
RIOS.description: Campus Drummers is an Afro-Caribbean drumming ensemble that meets the first Sunday of every month from 11am to 12noon. It is held in the Lunalilo Portables, Building 2, behind the UH Mānoa School of Music.

RIOS.name: Cannabis Club
RIOS.description: We got high hopes.

RIOS.name: Capoeira Senzala
RIOS.description: Our intention is to cultivate physically and mentally healthy individuals through the training and studying of Capoeira and other Brazilian traditions. We aim to develop citizens of the community by offering a dynamic philosophy and understanding of Honesty and Respect via the exploration and promotion of Brazilian culture through Capoeira.

RIOS.name: CARP Hawaii
RIOS.description: We are an organization of chapters on college campuses, created for students by students. We create programs, events, and activities promoting principles and raising leaders. Student leaders engage others in thoughtful and meaningful discussion as well as deep and long-lasting relationships for peace and growth.

RIOS.name: Change for Charity
RIOS.description: Change for Charities is a program designed to help teachers and students become more aware of world issues by providing lesson plans with resources, activities and service opportunities. Students can get involved by placing Change for Charity Jars in their classrooms, schools and in their communities. Companies can get involved by placing these jars in their buildings to support quality nonprofits and local schools programs. This allows the students, teachers and companies to support world issues and quality charities discussed in this program.

RIOS.name: Chemistry Club
RIOS.description: We are an undergraduate-run organization whose mission is to cultivate and enrich the interests of students studying chemistry at the university.

RIOS.name: Chess Club
RIOS.description: Currently we meet to play every Wednesday afternoon, usually in Campus Center 203. The exact details will be sent every Sunday, as they are slightly different week to week. All levels are welcome!

RIOS.name: Chi Epsilon
RIOS.description: In the spring of 1922 two groups of civil engineering students at the University of Illinois, one calling itself Chi Epsilon, and the other calling itself Chi Delta Chi, independently of each other, took steps to petition the faculty for permission to establish an honorary civil engineering fraternity. As soon as the existence of the two groups became known to each other, plans were immediately propagated to merge the two groups. On May 22, 1952, the Chi Epsilon Fraternity was founded. Since then, Chi Epsilon has grown to 133 chapters (of which 125 are active), with over 106,368 initiated members as of September 2009.

RIOS.name: Chinese Students and Scholars Association
RIOS.description: The Chinese Student and Scholar Association of the University of Hawai'i (CSSA-UH) is an officially registered independent organization (RIOs) of Chinese students and scholars from all over the world. It is non-profit, non-partisan, religion-free, and democratically self-governed. It serves as a community-based social organization for friendship and mutual assistance among its members and friends. It encourages its members to communicate and improve friendship among the peoples of China, America, and the rest of the world. It works for opening, equality, fairness and transparency in public life.

RIOS.name: Chinese Xiqu Club
RIOS.description: Want to learn singing and martial skills of traditional Chinese theatre? Come to Chinese Xiqu club in University of Hawaii at manoa!

RIOS.name: Church in Honolulu
RIOS.description: The church in Honolulu started when a small group of believers in this island took the stand of oneness in the body of Christ and began to meet as the church in Honolulu in 1974. Since then, the Lord has been faithful in adding genuine children of God to the church. We continue to meet from house to house according to the pattern of the early church shown in Acts 2:46 until today.

RIOS.name: Circle K International
RIOS.description: CIRCLE K INTERNATIONAL (CKI) AT THE UNIVERSITY OF HAWAI`I AT MANOA WAS FOUNDED IN 1978. WE ARE A PREMIER COLLEGIATE COMMUNITY SERVICE CLUB, LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT, AND FRIENDSHIP ORGANIZATION THAT IS PART OF THE BIGGER GLOBAL CLUB COMMUNITY THAT IS KIWANIS. CKI IS COMPRISED OF COLLEGE AND UNIVERSITY STUDENTS WHO ARE RESPONSIBLE CITIZENS AND LEADERS WITH A LIFELONG COMMITMENT TO COMMUNITY SERVICE WORLDWIDE. WITH OVER 12,600 MEMBERS IN 17 NATIONS, CKI IS THE WORLD'S LARGEST COLLEGIATE SERVICE LEADERSHIP ORGANIZATION AND IS MAKING A POSITIVE IMPACT ON THE WORLD EVERY DAY.

RIOS.name: Clay Club
RIOS.description: We are the University Of Hawaii of Manoa Ceramics Club

RIOS.name: Clinical and Translational Research Program Student Organization at JABSOM
RIOS.description: UHM club for the Clinical and Translational Research Program.

RIOS.name: Club Management of America
RIOS.description: CMAA offers many opportunities for students to become acquainted with the club management profession and onto the path to leadership early. By joining CMAA, you have begun to take steps to further your professional development through meetings, events, practical experiences, internships, education and conferences.  Combined with classroom theories and networking with peers and managers, you are doing exactly what you need to do to be successful in the club industry. Being a CMAA student member is a great way to jump start your future!

RIOS.name: Coalition to Stop Campus Hunger
RIOS.description: UHM club for people who want to stop campus hunger.

RIOS.name: C.O.P. Alaka'ina
RIOS.description: COP Alaka`ina builds a sense of community and support among College Opportunities Program (COP) students and alumni through educational, social, and community service activities.  Alumni of COP act upon the upcoming COP year as a mentor to help with the transition into college by assisting with registration, campus involvement and more.

RIOS.name: Cru
RIOS.description: Hawaii Cru is at three campuses on the island of O'ahu, UH Manoa, Kapi'olani Community College and Leeward Community College.  We desire college students to learn how to live out, communicate, and multiply their faith to build the Kingdom of God.

RIOS.name: CTAHR Student Ambassadors
RIOS.description: Student Ambassadors are CTAHR student and alumni volunteers. It is the purpose of Student Ambassadors to recruit prospective students, to encourage student interest and participation in CTAHR, and to positively portray CTAHR to the University and community at large. Student Ambassadors represent the college in a variety of ways. They give presentations about college life, the different majors within CTAHR, and career opportunities available with a degree from CTAHR. They represent CTAHR at information and career/college fairs and are available for shadowing by prospective students. Ambassadors are available to travel to any high school or community college in the state of Hawai‘i to make a presentation. They are more than happy to take prospective students to their classes and on a tour of the UH Mānoa campus.

RIOS.name: Delta Sigma Pi, Rho Chi
RIOS.description: Delta Sigma Pi is a co-ed professional business fraternity organized to foster the study of business in universities and was founded on November 7, 1907 at New York University by Harold Valentine Jacobs, Alexander Frank Makay, Alfred Moysello and Henry Albert Tienken. With over 280,000 members and 200 collegiate chapters around the country, Delta Sigma Pi continues to develop principled business leaders for the future by providing a lifetime of opportunity for our members.

RIOS.name: Disney Ohana Club
RIOS.description: Aloha, and welcome to the Disney Ohana Club's official webpage!  The Disney Ohana Club at the University of Hawai`i at Mānoa is dedicated to providing students with a variety of opportunities that are offered to enhance their college career and promote professional-personal development through leadership, friendships, and community service.  Founded in Fall 2016, the Disney Ohana Club continues to grow with every new experience. Thank you for visiting our page and we hope to see you real soon!

RIOS.name: Emergency Medicine Interest Group
RIOS.description: UHM club for people interested in emergency medicine at the JABSOM.

RIOS.name: Engineering Ohana
RIOS.description: UHM club for students interested in the engineering program.

RIOS.name: Engineering Network
RIOS.description: Our mission is to interconnect engineering students and provide unique networking opportunities with other clubs at UH Manoa.

RIOS.name: Eta Kappa Nu
RIOS.description: Eta Kappa Nu (HKN) is the international honor society for electrical and computer engineers. It was founded at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign in 1904. Since then, it has grown to over 150 chapters across the globe. Members consist of students, alumni, and other professionals who have demonstrated exceptional academic and professional accomplishments. Student members are selected on the basis of scholastic standing, an impeccable character, and excellent leadership skills. The Delta Omega chapter of HKN was founded in 1963 at the University of Hawai'i at Manoa. Based in the islands of Hawai‘i, our mission is to encourage excellence within the electrical and computer engineering fields, as well as providing service to our community through volunteering and community service projects.

RIOS.name: Eta Sigma Delta
RIOS.description: Eta Sigma Delta (ESD) is an international hospitality honor society that recognizes the academic excellence of students pursuing a degree in hospitality, tourism and culinary arts. ESD members consist of students who have completed at least 50% of the credit hours for graduation, are of at least sophomore standing, have obtained a 3.0 or higher cumulative GPA, and are within the top 20 percentile of their class.  ESD focuses on a commitment to service. Student members work with groups including Ronald McDonald House Charities, Hawai’i Food Bank, and Na Ala Hele, organizing community service projects. ESD members pay a one time membership fee and host fundraisers to help subsidize costs of events for their members.

RIOS.name: Ethnic Studies Student Association
RIOS.description: The Ethnic Studies Student Association (ESSA) is a non-profit organization based at the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa.  Our central goal is to create an open dialogue about culture, identity, and socio-political issues that are explored in ethnic studies (ES) courses and in life. ESSA takes a critical stance against racism, sexism, homophobia, classism, and the systematic marginalization of people of color.

RIOS.name: Every Nation Campus Pearlside
RIOS.description: UHM club for the Pearlside church.

RIOS.name: Family Medicine Interest Group
RIOS.description: We are a group of UH JABSOM medical students interested in the primary care field of Family Medicine. FM focuses on values like continuity of care, community outreach and patient education. It is our goal for FMIG to reflect these same values.

RIOS.name: Financial Management Association
RIOS.description: Our mission is to provide our members with opportunities: to expand their knowledge of financial theory and its applications, to strengthen their social and professional network among peers and the business community and to develop their professional skill sets by providing our members with various socials, tours and workshops.

RIOS.name: Food Science and Human Nutrition Council
RIOS.description: ALOHA, come join us in AgSci 219 every month to meet and network with fellow FSHN students– ranging from food science majors to dietetics majors. At each monthly meeting we join together to discuss how FSHN council can make a positive impact on the community through volunteering and educating the public. Through FSHN council you will stay informed about many career building opportunities, professional networking outings and much more. Come assist in bake sales and the food recovery network. Our meetings typically consist of discussing upcoming volunteer events (bring your calendars), a guest speaker or two and yummy foods to devour while we meet!

RIOS.name: Formula SAE Rainbow Warrior Racing
RIOS.description: Formula SAE is an international collegiate competition, in which students from universities around the globe work in teams to design, build, and compete with a formula-style racecar. This type of competition requires students to use classroom knowledge for a real life project. By the end of the project, students will be able to gain skills, knowledge, and abilities in which no engineering, automotive, or business course could replace. The Rainbow Warrior Racing Team at the University of Hawai’i at Mānoa was developed from the mechanical engineering undergraduate senior design course. We have created a program that will allow underclassmen students to shadow upperclassmen in order to continue this project in their senior design course. We have also opened the team to anyone who attends the university in hopes to expand our knowledge and perspectives contributing to our project. As a result, our team has become more diverse with over 30 students coming from different disciplines, ethnic groups, and ages.

RIOS.name: Freestyle Dance Club
RIOS.description: UHM club for students interested in freestyle dance.

RIOS.name: Friends of the Family
RIOS.description: The Friends of the Family (FOF) at the University of Hawai'i at Mānoa is a student-operated club, consisting of officer positions and a general member body. Our mission is to motivate college students in giving back to individuals and families through service in the local community.

RIOS.name: Generation Action at the University of Hawai'i at M?noa
RIOS.description: Planned Parenthood Generation Action is a non-partisan, not-for-profit student organization that advocates for social welfare and legislative issues that impact reproductive health care and education at UH Mānoa. We engage in activities regarding issues on legislative advocacy, voter education campaigns, and political action. We also work to preserve reproductive freedom and justice, and to elect representatives who will do the same. Our mission is to create a personally and politically safe climate in which individuals have universal and unfettered access to sexual and reproductive health services and are free to follow their own beliefs, values, and moral code when making decisions about these services.

RIOS.name: Glass Art Family
RIOS.description: The Glass Art Family at UH Manoa is a student-run organization at the University of Hawaii at Manoa. It is our mission to advance the education of art students and community members in the state of Hawaii. We work with artists across the state and internationally to promote the appreciation and development of glass as an art medium. We find funding to bring visiting artists, provide tools and equipment to the UH Glass Studio for member use, and help to provide further education beyond the classroom experience. Club members meet to discuss events, review portfolios, write and revise scholarship applications and grants, share new works in glass, and we hold the occasional social gathering.

RIOS.name: Golden Key International Honour Society
RIOS.description: Membership into the Society is by invitation only and applies to the top 15% of college and university sophomores, juniors and seniors, as well as top-performing graduate students in all fields of study, based solely on their academic achievements. As an international honor society with more than 400 chapters at colleges and universities around the world, Golden Key is committed to a high standard of scholastic achievement, and an ethos of integrity, innovation, respect, collaboration and diversity.  Golden Key offers its members exclusive opportunities and connections through over half a million dollars in scholarships and awards, partnerships with major corporations, career advancement, and graduate programs. The Society also works with university faculty and administrators to develop and maintain one of the highest standards of education in the world.

RIOS.name: Graduate Arts Council
RIOS.description: The Graduate Arts Council (GAC) is the department recognized voting body of ART graduate students governed as a University Recognized Organization (URO) to decide graduate student matters within the department. One elected Graduate Art Council (GAC) officer will represent the ART graduate students on the Graduate Committee and faculty meetings. The GAC representative is a full voting member of the Graduate Committee (on general policy recommendations but not individual student petitions) and an attendee of faculty meetings. In all cases the GAC member will act as a contributing member and active liaison with the GAC and is to report back to graduate students on important developments.

RIOS.name: Graduate Business Student Association
RIOS.description: The Graduate Business Student Association (GBSA) is made up of graduate students at the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa, Shidler College of Business. GBSA organizes professional, social, and community service events that spark lasting relationships between all members of the Shidler community.

RIOS.name: Graduate Hui Ola Pono
RIOS.description: Hui Ola Pono is the student group of the University of Hawaii at Manoa Office of Public Health Studies. The Hui provides a vehicle for public health students to present the ideas, interests, and concerns of the members of the student body. It serves as a liaison between the students, faculty, and administration. The Hui facilitates communication and involvement among students through scheduled meetings, coordination of social and educational activities, and dissemination of necessary information. It is an organization that provides students with opportunities to promote Public Health within both the university and Hawai’i community at large through outreach, education, and fundraising. This group provides support and guidance for incoming students and links students in the Public Health program with other students and Public Health professionals locally, nationally, and internationally.

RIOS.name: Graduate Student Sociological Association
RIOS.description: The Graduate Student Sociological Association (GSSA) was established to provide graduate students in Sociology at the UH Mānoa with professional, social and cultural support, a forum for discussion about student issues, and official representation in the Department of Sociology. The association conducts a variety of professional and social activities among graduate students. Among these activities include orientations for new students, workshops on professional development and teaching, and a wide range of outings and get-togethers. The GSSA is a unique vehicle for current graduate students to help newcomers adjust to life in graduate school and beyond.

RIOS.name: Graduate Women in Science Hawaii
RIOS.description: Aloha, e komo mai! We are Graduate Women in Science Hawai'i (GWISH), and our mission is to support and honor the past, present, and future women scientists of Hawai‘i and the Pacific Region.  We unite multiple disciplines and diverse backgrounds to celebrate women and girls in their personal and professional endeavors as scientists, individuals, and community members. To this end, we provide a collaborative network of inspired and practicing scientists, professional development to strengthen women’s contributions to science, and a community presence to nurture the leaders of tomorrow.

RIOS.name: Grey Hats at UHM
RIOS.description: The Grey Hats is a student-led, extracurricular organization focused on real-world training for cyber defense. Membership gives students an outstanding opportunity to learn and apply critical skills, attack and defend systems, and to network with others interested in modern security issues.

RIOS.name: Hanwoori Hawaii
RIOS.description: Hanwoori is a student community that strives to connect UH students interested in Korean culture and language with peers and Korean exchange students

RIOS.name: Hawaii African Dance and Drum Club RIO at UHM
RIOS.description: Sewa Fare' (say-wa-fah-day) West African Dance & Drum Group.Sewa Fare' means joyful celebration in the language of sou sou (su su).The group includes master drummers from Guinea, who eloquently bring their culture to the Hawaiian Island through the rhythms of their drums. Dancers have studied in Guniea and have been performing on Oahu for more than 10 years. The drummers and dancers blend together to bring you an amazing energetic story.

RIOS.name: Hawaii Chapter of the Society for Conservation Biology
RIOS.description: HI-SCB is a new local chapter of the Society for Conservation Biology (SCB). "An international professional organization dedicated to promoting the scientific study of the phenomena that affect the maintenance, loss, and restoration of biological diversity."As a chapter of the larger organization, we share the vision and values of SCB, and try to focus on how to apply them locally. We are a professional organization grad students, undergraduates, post docs, residents, cultural practitioners and professionals in Hawaii dedicated to promoting the science and practice of conservation biology.  HI-SCB's board is based on Oahu, however our chapter is unique in that we are a SCB chapter covering multiple islands.  We encourage and support active participation to all interested parties and are pursuing represtation from all neighboring islands.

RIOS.name: Hawaii Educational Research Association
RIOS.description: The Hawai‘i Educational Research Association (HERA) provides a forum for sharing issues, insights, and research findings with educational researchers, administrators, teachers, and others who want to improve educational practice. Through its annual conference, publications, and periodic forums, HERA is a source of information for concerned educators in Hawai‘i. HERA also sponsors the Pacific Educational Research Journal, a refereed journal published annually. HERA is a member of the Consortium of State and Regional Educational Research Associations, an affiliate of the American Educational Research Association.

RIOS.name: Hawaii H.O.M.E. Project
RIOS.description: The mission of the Hawaii H.O.M.E. Project is to improve quality and access to health care for Hawaii’s homeless, while increasing student and physician awareness and understanding of the homeless and their healthcare needs. The project was founded in August of 2005 and currently provides free medical services to sheltered and unsheltered homeless individuals, through weekly student-run free clinics per at nine sites across Oahu. In addition to these clinics, we also utilize our mobile health van for outreach to other unsheltered homeless populations on Oahu and to provide special events for the keiki at the shelters.

RIOS.name: Hawaii Shotokan Karate
RIOS.description: Karate dojo at UHM.

RIOS.name: Hawaii Streams and Ecosystems
RIOS.description: UHM club for people interested in Hawaii streams and ecosystems.

RIOS.name: Hawaii Student Entrepreneurs
RIOS.description: Hawai’i Student Entrepreneurs was formed with the mission to inspire students to be entrepreneurs and to support them in starting and growing their own businesses. We strive not only to empower our members with the skills, knowledge, network, and resources to start and run a successful business now, but to also be prepared to utilize community resources in the future and to continue their education for success after they’ve graduated. We are the future entrepreneurs of Hawai’i!

RIOS.name: Hawaii Undergraduate Initiative
RIOS.description: Hawaii Undergraduate Initiative (HUI) is a summer leadership program providing a free 3-credit summer college course for a select group of incoming freshmen at the University of Hawaii at Manoa. In addition to the summer course, HUI offers engaging and insightful workshops on using university resources, exploring academics/careers and developing writing/math skills. All HUI participating scholars will be paired with a Peer Mentor who will support and assist them in their transition from high school to college.

RIOS.name: Her Campus Hawaii
RIOS.description: In 2009, three smart, empowered, and fearless college women got together (shout out to Annie, Windsor and Stephanie!) and launched a plan to fill a huge hole in the media market: an online magazine dedicated to, written by, and focused on empowering, college women.

RIOS.name: High Intensity Athletics at UHM
RIOS.description: High Intensity Athletics is the newest cheerleading and acro and tumbling training program in Hawaii.  We are the program that provides elite training for elite athletes. Our program is invested in developing the whole athlete, not just physical skills but mentally, emotionally, and academically. We are set on producing not just good athletes, but great individuals within the Hawai’i community. HIA is a unique program in Hawaii where you actually learn from athletes that have made the transition to the next level. Instructors are either past or current collegiate and/or all star cheerleaders or acrobatics professionals with an intensive background in high level of training.

RIOS.name: Higher Education Student Association
RIOS.description: The EDEA program in the University of Hawai'i's College of Education provides graduates with a comprehensive understanding and critical analysis skills of the issues, both national and international, within education. EDEA, specifically, focuses on post-secondary education and prepares students for advanced careers within higher education administration.  With graduation comes the responsibility to give back to the communities that helped get us to this point. HESA, therefore, is not just a space for discussion, arbitration, and symposium; it is a avenue to give back to the larger Hawaiian community, whether it be through donation, research, and/or just talking story. Please see the Fundraising page for more information.  We collectively believe that working together creates an environment for reasoning, analysis, and development. HESA helps get us started.

RIOS.name: HOSA at UHM
RIOS.description: Hawaii HOSA has come a long way since being officially recognized as a state association during the 2005-2006 school year. From 210 members representing 13 chapters to 1282 members representing 32 chapters, our membership count has increased every year. As one of the five Career and Technical Student Organizations in Hawaii (HOSA, DECA, FCCLA, FFA, and SkillsUSA), Hawaii HOSA provides opportunities for secondary and postsecondary students develop character and apply leadership skills within the context of the healthcare industry. It gives an avenue for students interested in health and medical careers to demonstrate their understanding of knowledge, skills, and attitudes that are expected in such a demanding field. The mission of Hawaii HOSA is to support and encourage students thirsting for knowledge, as well as produce individuals who will serve in the fight against illness and disease by entering the health professions. Hawaii HOSA provides its members with outlets for creativity and leadership through service projects, competitive events, and leadership positions in their respective chapters.

RIOS.name: Hui Dui
RIOS.description: Hui Dui officers develop their leadership skills by representing the students of LIS. They attend faculty meetings to provide a voice for the student body. They plan workshops of current interest and celebrate the achievements of the LIS graduates as they go out into the world...

RIOS.name: Hui M?lama Honua
RIOS.description: RIO at UHM interested in community outreach and engagement. Connecting our community with the Hawaiian way. One Earth. One Heart. In Motion.

RIOS.name: Hui Ola Pono
RIOS.description:
Hui Ola Pono is the student group of the University of Hawaii at Manoa Office of Public Health Studies. 
The Hui provides a vehicle for public health students to present the ideas, interests, and concerns of the members of the student body. It serves as a liaison between the students, faculty, and administration. The Hui facilitates communication and involvement among students through scheduled meetings, coordination of social and educational activities, and dissemination of necessary information. It is an organization that provides students with opportunities to promote Public Health within both the university and Hawai’i community at large through outreach, education, and fundraising. This group provides support and guidance for incoming students and links students in the Public Health program with other students and Public Health professionals locally, nationally, and internationally.

RIOS.name: Ilima Sacnas Chapter at UH
RIOS.description: Welcome to the University of Hawai'i 'Ilima SACNAS Chapter fanpage. This chapter is for all science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) students, faculty, and staff at Oahu colleges and universities.

RIOS.name: Information Technology Management Association
RIOS.description: Our mission is to strengthen the social and professional network between members in the Information Technology Management Association, alumni, and professionals by focusing on the development of quality relationships. ITMA is motivated and dedicated to provide its members with social and professional relationships, provide access to technical resources, and be an example of a growing technical environment to foster career development.

RIOS.name: Interactive Story Telling Club
RIOS.description: UHM club for learning about Interactive Story Telling.

RIOS.name: Inter-Business Council
RIOS.description: The Inter-Business Council has been bringing leaders together since 1970. Our mission is to serve as a liaison between Shidler students, faculty and Shidler Alumni Association.

RIOS.name: International Business Organization
RIOS.description: The International Business Organization (IBO) was created by two international students, Billy Wu and Ivan Lam, in 2010. We are the foremost club promoting the study of international business and culture at the Shidler College of Business. IBO develops international excellence within our members through a combination of professional development, networking, philanthropy, and cultural awareness.

RIOS.name: International Student Association
RIOS.description: The International Student Association (ISA in the 1960’s and 70’s), the Peer Advocates (PAS – 1980-87), the Peer Advocate Leadership Society (PALS – 1999-2003), and the current International Student Association (ISA – 2003-the present time) were all established with a common goal. That was to provide a support system for international students attending the University of Hawai’i. Through these years, International Student leaders came together foster the common goals which were finally written down in its first constitution in 1999. This constitution established an operating framework for the organization and is still followed to this day. In 2003, PALS members voted to re-name itself as the International Student Association.

RIOS.name: Internal Medicine Interest Group
RIOS.description: The Internal Medicine Interest Group (IMIG) at the University of Hawaii John A. Burns School of Medicine (UH JABSOM) was founded in 2006. Since its inception, it has been one of the most active and largest student interest groups at the school. Even before our IMIG was founded in 2006, UH JABSOM had won ACP Medical School Awards for student membership ranging 58-74.5% of the student body. The founding of IMIG in spring 2006 has resulted in record high levels of ACP student membership, ranging 77-83%. Our goals are to provide medical students with information about careers in internal medicine, foster communication with faculty, connect students with shadowing and research opportunities, and improve clinical skills and knowledge applicable to internal medicine.

RIOS.name: Intervarsity Christian Fellowship
RIOS.description: Welcome to the InterVarsity Hawai‘i website. We are an inter-denominational Christian fellowship for students of all ethnic and cultural backgrounds. Whether you have been a follower all your life, or simply open to Jesus, we invite you to come and experience God's love.

RIOS.name: Institute of Electrical and Electronic Engineers
RIOS.description: IEEE at UHM is a student-led club on campus for all majors. We are an associated student organization with ECUH and a registered RIO with the university. Our club room is located in HH411. Throughout the year, we hold various professional and casual events for our members to enjoy. Whether you want to learn how to program, solder, or just have fun we have events for all occasions. Come check us out!

RIOS.name: Jehovah's Witnesses at the University of Hawai'i - Manoa
RIOS.description: THe UHM group for Jehovah's Witnesses.

RIOS.name: Judo Club/Team at University of Hawaii at Manoa
RIOS.description: The “Judo Club/Team at the University of Hawaii” is a Registered Independent Organization (RIO) of the University of Hawaii at Manoa. The club/team is open to registered students or affiliates of the University of Hawaii at Manoa.

RIOS.name: K-Mixx Club
RIOS.description: UHM club for students interested in K-pop.

RIOS.name: Ka Lau O Ka Lahui
RIOS.description: N/A

RIOS.name: Ka Lama Kukui Interest Group
RIOS.description: Ka Lama Kukui, "The Light of the Kukui Tree," was given this name since the kukui tree is the kinolau of Kane, the god of healing and fresh water, and lama means light, knowledge, and wisdom. Our goal is to perpetuate the light that has been given to us.

RIOS.name: K?lai Pohaku
RIOS.description: Program focused on increasing Native Hawaiians & Pacific Islanders pipelines into engineering academic pathways thru empowerment, advocacy and training.

RIOS.name: Ka Mea Kolo Entomology Club
RIOS.description: The members of Ka Mea Kolo are entomophilic and enjoy sharing our understanding and enthusiasm for the earth's most diverse creatures especially those that have made Hawai'i their home.  The Lorax spoke for the trees (Dr. Seuss 1971) .  We speak for the insects.  Ka Mea Kolo is a student organization at the University of Hawai'i at Manoa in the College of Tropical Agriculture and Human Resources. We provide presentations to school groups and community organizations around Oahu.  Invite us to come and give a presentation to your group.  Become a member.  Join us at one of our activities. Tap into the resources that we have gathered together for those interested in entomology.  Any questions, please contact us and we will do our best to assist you.

RIOS.name: Kanoa
RIOS.description: We're a Bible based club that's open to anyone to come and check out! We mainly do a bunch of random activities together like beach days, game nights, etc while doing our best to make the environment comfortable for all!

RIOS.name: Kappa Sigma
RIOS.description: Kappa Sigma at the University of Hawai‘i at Manoa– designated “Omicron Zeta” – received its charter on October 29, 2005. Since then it has been among the top on-campus organizations and the foremost fraternity at UH with brothers participating in student government, ROTC, and other prominent extra-curricular activities. The chapter has also donated time and money to various charitable organizations including Hawai‘i Habitat for Humanity, the Hawai'ian Humane Society, the Blood Bank of Hawai‘i, and the American Cancer Society.

RIOS.name: Katipunan Club
RIOS.description: The University of Hawaii at Manoa Katipunan Club is comprised of all students currently enrolled in the Filipino Language & Philippine Literature Program courses offered at the University of Hawaii.

RIOS.name: Kempo Club at UHM
RIOS.description: Kempo Club at the University of Hawaii at Manoa (Kempo Club at UHM)* is a new club practicing the art of Kempo. We emphasize personalized instruction in a friendly, non-competitive, but challenging atmosphere.

RIOS.name: Kim's Tae Kwon Do @ UHM
RIOS.description: Kim's Tae Kwon Do at Hawaii is an official part of Kim's United Tae Kwon Do Federation, which is the largest Tae Kwon Do federation in the North Western United States. The head instructor of the Hawaii branch is Mr Mason Nakadomari who is a 3rd degree black belt. There are three schools under the Hawaii Branch located in University of Hawaii at Manoa and Ewa beach.

RIOS.name: Kinesiology and Rehabilitation Sciences Club
RIOS.description: The broad goals are to provide students with connections/networking among other KRS majors and information that will further the success of participants in the kinesiology field. The aims of this organization are to strengthen the social aspect of community among students in the KRS department. In addition, our organization will be dedicated in participating in community/volunteer service hours. These service hours will not only create community engagement but will also help members receive interactive experiences showing the opportunities that can be achieved with a Kinesiology and Rehabilitation Science Bachelor’s degree.

RIOS.name: Korean Drama Interest Group
RIOS.description: UHM club for students interested in Korean dramas.

RIOS.name: La Raza Unida
RIOS.description: The UHM club for La Raza Unida.

RIOS.name: Lifesaver Club
RIOS.description: The Lifesaver Club at UH Manoa is dedicated to assisting in efforts to provide a safe and adequate supply of blood for Hawaii's growing blood needs.

RIOS.name: Living Stone Chinese Christian Fellowship
RIOS.description: You are invited to join us to celebrate God's love and grace!  Hear Good News and come here to have an abundant life!
